ave the diagram unless I found some spells that were stolen from him by the giant.<br>Barely keeping my anger in check, I told him that it wasn't my fault he lost his damned spells but he was adamant about it.  I resolved to finish this task for Lord Qyzar and then deal with this fool afterwards.<br><br>I collected Myrdukk and Sorla and we headed out into the woods, waiting for nightfall before the final approach. We found the fort without a problem; it was just down the road past the stream like the spy told us.  We were hoping for a bit of lax security on the part of the stupid brutes but were disappointed at finding the gate guarded.  Good thing we were prepared.<br><br>We swung over to the western fort wall, where the spy told us the giants patrolled least.  After several heaves Myrdukk was finally able to secure the grapple across the parapet and we hauled ourselves over.  Rapelling down into the fort we spread out to scout the area.  <br><br>Apparently the giants entrusted their gate guards with the security of the place as we found no roving patrols within.  Sorla was the first to report good news.  She had found a house on the northern edge which contained some of the smaller giants the spy told us about; the saplings which "stole" his scrolls.<br><br>We made a final plan then slowly and carefully entered the house.  The stink was incredible.  I thought the Burynai breath was bad, but it was nothing compared to a pile of sleeping giants.  Did these beings eat only rotten meat?<br><br>Our initial plan was to dispatch the giants one by one, but their proximity to each other would entail the chance of one being woken by the wounded cries of another, so we quickly decided to dispatch them all at once, there being one for each of us.<br><br>I picked my victim from the three and crept up until I was beside it's head.  For this task I left my Khukri sheathed; it was a potent weapon but a little too short for this work.  Instead I had a longsword ready and I slowly raised it until the tip was very close to the sleeping giant's head.  I looked around at the others who each gave me an affirmative nod.<br><br>I gave a nod back and with all my strength pushed the blade of the longsword as hard as I could into the giant's ear.  It slid in easily.  The sleeping giant opened it's eyes and drew it's breath sharply as if to scream in pain, but instead the air escaped slowly from it's now lifeless chest.<br><br>Myrdukk's blade must have glanced off a bone as his giant sat up suddenly, a bloody blade embedded in it's ear, throwing Myrdukk to the ground.  Luckily Sorla was done with hers and leapt at the sitting giant and cleaved it's neck with her blade.  The giant turned it's head to look at this new source of torment but then fell lifeless among the others.<br><br>"Quickly!" I hissed "Search them and we go!"<br><br>We fell upon the dead giants, rifling through their rank clothing until we found what we were after.  Two battered scrolls both being used as wrappings for foraged roots were on the giant Sorla had dispatched.  I spied outside and seeing the way clear bade the others to follow.  We made the wall in good order then quickly climbed the rope we had left behind and exited the foul place.<br><br>I returned to the spy and gave him the scrolls for which he gave me the diagram in return.  One look at the diagram and I was livid with rage.<br><br>"This...this..scribbling!" I stammered in disbelief. "This child's drawing?  This is what we risked our lives to obtain?"<br><br>"But it took me days to draw this map." He was clearly surprised.<br><br>"You incompetent idiot!  I could draw a map ten times better than this and all I have is one nighttime visit to the place!" I was waving his ugly little drawing in front of his face.<br><br>I turned to my companions to show them the drawing.  Instead of looking at it Sorla let out a laugh and pointed behind me.  Seizing this opportunity the spy had hightailed it out of the building.<br><br>"Probably for the best." I spoke. "It could have turned a bit bloody if he stayed.  Heh."<br><br>It took Myrdukk, Sorla, and I about an hour to draw a much better map of the giant fort, which we then presented to Lord Qyzar.  For our troubles we each received our new Khukris of the Zealot. <p><hr><center><b><font size="4" color="#FF0000">Carnifex</font></b><br><b><font color="#008000">Cazic's Crusader</font> - <a href="http://pub73.ezboard.com/bsullonzektavern">Sullon   Zek</a></b><br><b><font color="#008000">Scaled Mystic</font> - <a href="http://pub43.ezboard.com/btallonzektimes4735">Tallon   Zek</a></b><br><hr></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/uguri007.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Guri007</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/17/01 2:17:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> WOW</span><hr size=1> This is the absolute best game related role play I've ever read. Great job man. You should be in the buisness if you aren't already :-P <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/ucarnifexrex.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Carnifex Rex</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://guildhome.org/g/tinyskull.jpg BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tavern Regular</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/17/01 2:07:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://guildhome.org/tz/carnifex.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Crusader</span><hr size=1> I hold in my hand the princely sum of one hundred and fifty platinum pieces.  This would make me quite happy by itself, but unfortunately this only means I am still twelve hundred short.<br><br>Several nights I spoke to the Scarscales, the master Crusader blacksmiths.  I had heard a rumor of a new type of armor that they were developing and sought to query them.  I was received politely enough, but I noticed both of them became rather short with me after I disclosed I was quite broke.<br><br>"Tis true.  We can make you the Dreadscale armor but we require rare components in order to fashion it." Sarth Scarscale informed me.  "Also, each piece will require a gem or two to be ground and the powder combined with the metal in the forge.  We estimate the gems alone will cost you over thirteen hundred platinum pieces."<br><br>I looked over the list of components required.  Bloodgill scales?  The head of Grachnist?  Ugh. <br><br>"Since we are in the smithing business, not the charity business, I am afraid you are wasting our time here."<br><br>Dismissed thusly, I wandered around thinking as to how I was going to come upon these riches.  I remembered Rossorik and what he told me several weeks after our meeting in the Tower of Kurn.  He said that he and his party made some nice cash selling the fine steel weapons they had acquired in the tower.  He mentioned that there was one area of the tower which seemed to be frequented by armed bones, and that some of them gave greater treasures still.<br><br>I had not been to Kurn's in quite a while but I still remembered my first encounter with the smelly Burynai.  I was sure that now that I have had my extensive training and experience the denizens of the tower would fall before me.  Emboldened, I made preparations to enter the tower.<br><br>For this trip I decided to go in alone.  As this would be a money making proposition I was loath to share my spoils.  I crossed the Bonefield and climbed the ramp.  Once in the tower, I made myself invisible to the bones and followed the directions Rossorik gave me; hug the right wall, down the double stairs, hug the left wall, down the curving stairs, then forward to the end and make a right.  <br><br>I had little trouble making it down and soon recognized the area where I first came upon Rossorik and his crew.  I made my camp there and got to work.<br><br>I stayed there for two weeks, sneaking out occasionally to refill my supplies and get rid of the accumulated loot.  I fought the undead and the badgers, all falling equally to my skilled strokes.  It wasn't glorious and it wasn't heroic, but it was very profitable.  Some of the bones wielded weapons made of fine steel, and this was my prime objective.  I also accumulated backpacks of hide and ruined scale armor, bronze weapons, gems, and other items which swelled my bank account.<br><br>One night while getting ready to rest for the evening I spied a strange light from down the hallway.  I got up to investigate and followed the source of the light.  It was a new bone, one I had never seen before.  While this bone was altogether unremarkable, I saw that it was armed with a shield.  It was this shield that was the source of the light.<br><br>There were two other bones in the room, but I knew that bones were quite stupid and was able to slay them once I enticed them singly out of the room, whereupon I set upon the shielded bone and smote it easily.  <br><br>I took my new prize and examined it.  I could see it was of higher quality than my current shield, and it was scribed with runes on the edges.  It was an ancient script, but after a time I was able to comprehend the nature of the magic.  In addition to the glowing light, the shield also provided some protection against spells.  This was good news indeed.<br><br>I noticed that on some days my little hunting ground got quite crowded.  Either Rossorik was loose with his tongue or there were more intrepid explorers than I thought, but either way some nights I had competition from over dozens of my fellows, all looking for the same thing; riches.<br><br>Unwilling to share the spoils, I approached none of them.  Instead I moved a little farther inwards where no one hunted.  Armed with the knowledge of the timing of the bone patrols, I was able to run in at a designated time and virtually pluck the patrolling bones from the grasp of the other hunters.  If the others were more observant, they would have noticed the bone patrols returning every seventeen and a half minutes.  As it were, I was the only one keeping time (apparently only I had the patience to count to one thousand and fifty), and I was able to move in just at the right time.  I gained no friends this way, but I already have an abundance of friends. <br><br>It is platinum that I lack. <p><hr><center><b><font size="4" color="#FF0000">Carnifex</font></b><br><b><font color="#008000">Cazic's Crusader</font> - <a href="http://pub73.ezboard.com/bsullonzektavern">Sullon   Zek</a></b><br><b><font color="#008000">Scaled Mystic</font> - <a href="http://pub43.ezboard.com/btallonzektimes4735">Tallon   Zek</a></b><br><hr></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/ucarnifexrex.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Carnifex Rex</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://guildhome.org/g/tinyskull.jpg BORDER=0> at: 7/17/01 2:11:55 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/ubreathepk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Breathe pk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/17/01 10:41:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crusader</span><hr size=1> /clap<br><br>very nice.<br><br>Please keep it up.<br> <p>Breathe <BR>Teir Dal Mage of Innoruuk<BR>SZ